              <h2>
                How this construction planning and estimating calculator works
              </h2>
              <p>
                This tool follows the same logic used in professional
                construction estimating software, but in a simplified,
                transparent format. You build your estimate from the bottom up:
                quantities, unit costs and production rates roll up into phase
                totals, which then roll up into the overall budget and schedule.
              </p>

              <h3>Core formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. Material cost</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Material cost} = \text{Quantity} \times \text{Unit
                  cost}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-3">
                  <strong>2. Crew days and labor hours</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Crew days} = \dfrac{\text{Quantity}}{\text{Production
                  rate per day}}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Labor hours} = \text{Crew days} \times \text{Crew
                  size} \times 8\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-3"><strong>3. Labor cost</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Labor cost} = \text{Labor hours} \times \text{Labor
                  rate}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-3"><strong>4. Line item total</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Line total} = \text{Material cost} + \text{Labor
                  cost}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-3"><strong>5. Direct cost</strong></p>
                <p>\(\text{Direct cost} = \sum \text{Line totals}\)</p>
                <p class="mt-3">
                  <strong>6. Contingency, overhead and profit</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Contingency} = \text{Direct cost} \times
                  \dfrac{\%C}{100}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Overhead} = \text{Direct cost} \times
                  \dfrac{\%O}{100}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Profit} = \text{Direct cost} \times \dfrac{\%P}{100}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Total bid} = \text{Direct cost} + \text{Contingency} +
                  \text{Overhead} + \text{Profit}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Step-by-step: building a construction estimate</h2>
              <h3>1. Define the project and estimate class</h3>
              <p>
                Start by naming your project and selecting the estimate class.
                Early conceptual estimates (Class D/E) rely on high-level
                assumptions and higher contingencies. Detailed pre-bid estimates
                (Class A/B) use measured quantities, vendor quotes and lower
                contingencies.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Break the work into phases and line items</h3>
              <p>Typical phases include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sitework</strong> – clearing, grading, utilities,
                  excavation, backfill.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Structure</strong> – foundations, slabs, framing,
                  structural steel.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Envelope</strong> – walls, roofing, windows, doors,
                  waterproofing.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interiors</strong> – partitions, finishes, ceilings,
                  flooring, casework.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>MEP</strong> – mechanical, electrical, plumbing, fire
                  protection.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Exterior works</strong> – paving, landscaping,
                  fencing, site lighting.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Under each phase, add line items such as “Concrete slab 4 in”,
                “Metal stud partition”, or “Asphalt paving”. For each line,
                enter the quantity, unit, unit cost, crew size, production rate
                and labor rate.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Use production rates for realistic labor</h3>
              <p>
                Instead of guessing labor hours, use production rates (e.g. 350
                sq ft/day for drywall, 10 cu yd/day for footing concrete). This
                is how professional estimators align labor with schedule.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Apply contingency, overhead and profit</h3>
              <p>
                Once direct costs are calculated, apply contingency to cover
                unknowns, overhead to cover indirect costs (office, supervision,
                insurance) and profit to reach your target margin. The
                calculator shows each component separately so you can explain
                your pricing.
              </p>

